The National Economic Council (NEC), Thursday, resolved to invest an additional $250 million in core capital into the Nigeria Sovereign Investment Authority (NSIA).Briefing State House Correspondent at the end of the 99th NEC meeting chaired by Vice President Yemi Osinbajo in Abuja, the Managing Director, NSIA, Mr Uche Orji said the Authority made a profit of N44.3billion in 2018 and N24billion from January to June 30th 2019 in spite of volatility in the global market due to the US/China trade disputes and Brexit.  Our Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan, reports that this would bring the total contribution to the Sovereign Wealth Fund from the federation to US$1.75 billion and represents the third contribution to the Authority from the current administration.   NEC also resolved that the "Governor of Kaduna State should chair an NEC Committee to consider how a portion of Pension Funds can also be leveraged into the investment for the NSIA with possible involvement of PENCOM.   Also speaking, Governor of Nassarawa, Abdullahi Sule disclosed that the Council resolved that the Governor of Ekiti State should constitute an Ad-hoc Committee involving Governors to engage with the Federal Ministry of Mines and Steel Development to find ways of addressing all the issues involved towards a beneficial development of the solid mineral sector.  On updates involving the Excess Crude Account (ECA), the Accountant General of the Federation told Council that â€œthe Excess Crude Account (ECA) balance as at 20th November 2019 stood at $324.54 million while the Stabilization Account balance was N29billion.